The paper deals with a machine learning algorithm that learns a reward function from demonstrations to complete a task. This falls under the category of artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The algorithm uses deep maximum entropy IRL, which is a type of deep learning, making it likely to fall under the category of machine learning (cs.LG). The task inference module infers the high-level memory structure of the task, which involves planning and decision-making, making it likely to fall under the category of robotics (cs.RO). The algorithm uses demonstrations to learn the reward function, which involves computer vision and image processing, making it likely to fall under the category of computer vision (cs.CV). Finally, the algorithm involves the use of a deterministic finite automaton (DFA), which is a type of control theory, making it likely to fall under the category of systems and control (cs.SY).
